Identification of Adolescents at Risk for Suicide Attempt¶

Elyse Llamocca

BMI 8050 Final Project

Autumn 2020

Project Description¶

Suicide and suicide attempts among youth are major public health concerns. Suicide is the second leading cause of death in those aged 10 to 14 in the United States, and the rate of suicide has been increasing. (1) Youth health care visits related to suicidal behavior, defined as suicidal ideation and/or suicide attempt, are also increasing in the United States. (2,3) History of suicide attempt is a strong predictor of subsequent suicide attempt and suicide death. (4-7) Prospective identification of youth at risk for suicide attempt is vital to allow targeted intervention efforts to prevent future suicide attempts or suicide death. Machine learning is a potential valuable tool to identify youth at risk for suicide attempt. As argued by Hill et al. in a study attempting to predict suicide attempt in adolescents using machine learning, "One key advantage of machine learning approaches is the ability to approaches is the ability to better account for large numbers of inter-related predictors and to examine all possible interactions between predictors. As a result, these techniques may be better able to model the complex interplay of suicide risk markers in a way that regression based models and human cognition often do not. (8)

Regression analyses and machine learning have been used to attempt to predict suicide attempts among United States youth in the past, including in combination with natural language processing and in both clinical and community-based settings. See, for example: Hill et al., Carson et al., Mich et al., Su et al., and Walsh et al. (8-12) Methods utilized to predict suicide attempts among United States youth in these examples included logistic regression, lasso logistic regression, ridge logistic regression, random forest, and classification tree. One interesting example is found in a study by Hill et al. (8), which utilized data from a nationally representative sample of adolescents in the United States to predict suicide attempters using classification tree analysis. Recognizing the importance of building a model to predict suicide attempts using nationally representative data, the objective of this project is to build upon Hill et al.s work by predicting suicide attempts among adolescents using nationally-representative data from the National Longitudinal Study of Adolescent to Adult Health (Add Health) using two additional methodologies, logistic regression with L1 regularization and neural networks.

This project will prioritize maximizing sensitivity, or the proportion of those with a suicide attempt correctly predicted as a suicide attempter, given the severity of the outcome and the importance of prospectively identifying those who will have a suicide attempt for intervention, while seeking to maintain as high of a specificity as possible. Specificity is defined as the proportion of those without a suicide attempt correctly predicted as non-suicide attempters. Hill et al. (8) identified the following classification tree model that had high sensitivity at the cost of specificity. This model predicted suicide attempt in 31.5% of the sample (174/192 of those who attempted suicide; 1,351 false positives), with a sensitivity of 90.6%, a specificity of 70.9%, and an accuracy of 71.7%. It required 9 unique pieces of information. Models such as this which, due to the lower specificity, have a high number of false positives may perhaps be more useful in settings where intervention is less resource intensive but still effective.

Classification Tree with High Sensitivity at Cost of Specificity from Hill et al.¶

To allow comparison of results, I attempted to follow Hill et al.s (all future references to Hill et al. refer to Reference #8 above) methodology as closely as possible. I obtained Wave 1 (1994-1995; n=6,054) and Wave 2 (1996; n=4,834) Add Health Public Use data and associated code and documentation from the Inter-University Consortium for Political and Social Research (ICPSR), as did Hill et al. The Add Health Public Use Data consists of a random subsample from the original nationally representative sample. The final analytic sample included all 4,834 individuals who responded to both Wave 1 and Wave 2. Hill et al. considered all adolescent self-response variables from the Wave 1 for inclusion as independent variables. These variables represent a wide range of data, including demographic, socioeconomic, social/family, psychological, physical health, and environmental factors. Variables were excluded if Hill et al. considered them uninterpretable or if they were missing more than 20% of data. My analysis used the same 345 variables identified for inclusion by Hill et al. The dependent variable was dichotomous, indicating whether a respondent had any reported suicide attempts during the past 12 months at Wave 2. In the final dataset, 192 individuals (~4.0%) had any reported suicide attempts during the past 12 months at Wave 2.

For all variables except past year suicide attempts (as reported at both Wave 1 and Wave 2), responses of missing, refused, don't know, not applicable, and legitimate skip were recoded as missing. Since past suicide attempt is a strong predictor of future suicide attempt, responses of legitimate skip for past year suicide attempts at Wave 1 and Wave 2 were recoded as 0.

The SAS code shown below was used to create an initial cleaned data set.

SAS Code for Data Cleaning¶

libname lib "C:\Users\Elyse's Flippy PC\Desktop\Machine Learning\Project\From ICPSR\Project Data";

proc import datafile="C:\Users\Elyse's Flippy PC\Desktop\Machine Learning\Project\From ICPSR\Project Data\wave1.tsv"
out=lib.wave1 dbms=tab replace;
run;

proc cimport
infile="C:\Users\Elyse's Flippy PC\Desktop\Machine Learning\Project\From ICPSR\Project Data\wave2.stc" lib=work;
run;

proc cimport
infile="C:\Users\Elyse's Flippy PC\Desktop\Machine Learning\Project\From ICPSR\Project Data\wave2_weights.stc" lib=work;
run;

tables H2SU2*H2SU2_recode;

by aid;

by aid;

by aid;
run;

merge merged_data(in=a) sample_weights(in=b);

if a=1 and b=1;
run;

Splitting into Training and Testing Data¶

This code splits the data into 80% training, 20% testing, keeping the distribution of the outcome variable (any suicide attempt in the past 12 months at Wave 2; h2su2) the same between the testing and training datasets.

In [4]:
pd.options.mode.chained_assignment = None

properties = list(df.columns.values)
properties.remove('h2su2') #remove outcome
properties.remove('AID') #remove id number
properties.remove('GSWGT2') #remove weight
print('number of independent variables in full dataset:',len(properties))
X = df[properties]
Y = df['h2su2']

#print(X.head)
#print(Y.head)

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, Y,test_size=0.2, random_state=1000,stratify=Y)

#print(x_test.head)

Data Preprocessing¶

The following code imputes missing data. For continuous variables, missing values are imputed as the mean. For categorical variables, missing values are imputed as the most frequent category.

In [7]:

cat_imp = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')
for c in cat_columns:
  x_train[c] = cat_imp.fit_transform(x_train[[c]]).ravel()
for c in cat_columns: 
  x_train[c] = x_train[c].astype(int)
for c in num_columns:
  x_train[c] = mean_imp.fit_transform(x_train[[c]]).ravel()

for c in cat_columns:
  x_test[c] = cat_imp.fit_transform(x_test[[c]]).ravel()
for c in cat_columns: 
  x_test[c] = x_test[c].astype(int)
for c in num_columns:
  x_test[c] = mean_imp.fit_transform(x_test[[c]]).ravel()

The following code performs one hot encoding for categorical variables, dropping one category to allow for the intercept in logistic regression models. The code also standardizes continuous variables.

# For each column that exists in the training dataset that is not in the testing dataset, create 
# a new column with all values set to 0
train_columns=x_train_df.columns

for column in train_columns:
    if column not in x_test_df.columns:
        x_test_df[column] = 0
        
# Reorder columns according to fixed columns
x_test_df = x_test_df[train_columns]

print('updated number of columns in testing data:',len(x_test_df.columns))

updated number of columns in testing data: 478

One key challenge with this dataset is that it is very imbalanced. Only about 4% of the sample has the outcome of interest. I will try several methods to manage the imbalanced data. These include:

1) Using class weights, where the class weight for each class is equal to ({1/number of observations in class} * total 
   observations)/2.0

2) Resampling methods

   -Randomly undersample the majority class

   -Randomly oversample the minority class

   -SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling Technique) + TOMEK (Undersampling)

The code below creates the resampled training datasets.

In [13]:
#Random undersampling
from imblearn.under_sampling import RandomUnderSampler
rus = RandomUnderSampler(random_state=1000)
x_rus, y_rus = rus.fit_sample(x_train_df, y_train)

#Random oversampling
from imblearn.over_sampling import RandomOverSampler
ros = RandomOverSampler(sampling_strategy='minority',random_state=1000)
x_ros, y_ros = ros.fit_sample(x_train_df, y_train)

#SMOTE (Oversampling) / TOMEK (Undersampling)

from imblearn.combine import SMOTETomek
stomek = SMOTETomek (random_state=1000)
x_stomek, y_stomek = stomek.fit_sample(x_train_df, y_train)

#Check distribution of outcomes in resampled training datasets
print('Random Undersampling','\n')
y_rus_df = pd.DataFrame(y_rus)
print(y_rus_df['h2su2'].value_counts(normalize=True))

print('Random Oversampling','\n')
y_ros_df = pd.DataFrame(y_ros)
print(y_ros_df['h2su2'].value_counts(normalize=True))

print('SMOTE/TOMEK','\n')
y_stomek_df = pd.DataFrame(y_stomek)
print(y_stomek_df['h2su2'].value_counts(normalize=True))

Training and Evaluating Logistic Regression Models¶

The following code trains and evaluates logistic regression models with L1 regularization (lasso logistic regression). L1 regularization was chosen over L2 regularization as L1 regularization creates coefficients of zero for specific variables. This might limit the number of variables needed to be collected, reducing the burden of collecting data to implement a model in a real-world setting in the future. I trained each set of models using four training datasets: 1) original training data with class weights described above, 2) training data with random undersampling of the majority class, 3) training data with random oversampling of the minority class, and 4) training data resampled using SMOTE + TOMEK.

For each of the 4 training datasets, four values of C were attempted: 0.005, 0.01, 0.05, and 0.10. C, the inverse of regularization strength, is a hyperparameter input into the code for logistic regression. Smaller values of C equal stronger regularization, which means that the coefficients of more variables become zero. The values of C were selected based on exploratory training and evaluation of models fit using the original training data with class weights. These values both meaningfully decreased the number of selected features, limiting the number of variables that would need to be collected to implement this model in a real-world setting, but gave good examples of possible performance of the model across difference values of C.

Evaluation of each logistic regression model was performed with the same testing dataset. The probability threshold for prediction of suicide attempt was shifted to change sensitivity and specificity values. The first threshold evaluated in each example is the threshold that gives the maximum F1 score. For each threshold, a confusion matrix is shown, and sensitivity, specificity, precision, F1 score, and accuracy were reported. For the final presentation, metrics were reported for a sensitivity equal to 0.92, but this written report demonstrates a wide range of different thresholds with varying sensitivity and specificity. I chose to use a sensitivity of 0.92 as an example because, while it is a high sensitivity that leads to correct prediction of many youth who will have a suicide attempt, it likely maintains a moderate specificity in order to keep a reasonable number of false positives.

Original Dataset with Class Weights¶

The following code calculates the class weights described above. The formula for the weight of each class is: ({1/number of observations in class} * total observations)/2.0. A suggestion found in the TensorFlow tutorial "Classification on Imbalanced Data" stated that scaling by total/2 helps keep the loss to a similar magnitude.

In [14]:
weight_for_0=(1/4642)*(4834)/2.0
weight_for_1=(1/192)*(4834)/2.0
class_weight={0:weight_for_0,1:weight_for_1}
print('Weight for non-suicide attempters: {:.2f}'.format(weight_for_0))
print('Weight for suicide attempters: {:.2f}'.format(weight_for_1))

Weight for non-suicide attempters: 0.52
Weight for suicide attempters: 12.59

print('Best Threshold=%f, F-Score=%.3f' % (lr_thresholds[ix], fscore[ix]))

In [18]:
def logistic_eval(threshold):
    log_predictions_df1=pd.DataFrame(log_predictions)
    log_predictions_df=log_predictions_df1.rename(columns={0: 'probability'})
    log_predictions_df['suicide_attempt'] = np.nan
    log_predictions_df['suicide_attempt'] = np.where(log_predictions_df['probability']>=threshold, 1, 0)
    final_predictions=log_predictions_df['suicide_attempt']

    c=confusion_matrix(y_test, log_predictions_df['suicide_attempt'])
    recall=c[1,1] / (c[1,1] + c[1,0])
    precision=c[1,1]/(c[0,1]+c[1,1])
    print('Confusion matrix when threshold=',threshold,'\n',c)
    print('Sensitivity/recall when threshold =',threshold, ':', recall)
    print('Specificity when threshold =',threshold, ':', c[0, 0] / (c[0, 1] + c[0, 0]))
    print('Precision when threshold =',threshold,':',precision)
    print('F1 Score when threshold =',threshold,':',(2*precision*recall)/(precision+recall))
    print('Accuracy when threshold =',threshold,':',(c[0,0]+c[1,1])/(c[0,0]+c[0,1]+c[1,0]+c[1,1]))
    print('\n')
    return

log_predictions = log_predictions1[:, 1]

# calculate precision and recall for each threshold
lr_precision, lr_recall, lr_thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, log_predictions)

#calculate the best threshold
# convert to f score
fscore = (2 * lr_precision * lr_recall) / (lr_precision + lr_recall)
# locate the index of the largest f score
ix = np.argmax(fscore)
print('Best Threshold=%f, F-Score=%.3f' % (lr_thresholds[ix], fscore[ix]))

sel_ = SelectFromModel(LogisticRegression(C=0.005, penalty='l1',solver='liblinear',random_state=1000,max_iter=500))

      np.sum(sel_.estimator_.coef_ == 0)))

In [43]:
test_x_new = sel_.transform(x_test_df)
test_selected_features = pd.DataFrame(sel_.inverse_transform(test_x_new), 
                                 index=x_test_df.index,
                                 columns=x_test_df.columns)

#calculate the predicted probabilities
log_predictions1=log_model.predict_proba(test_selected_features)
log_predictions = log_predictions1[:, 1]

# calculate precision and recall for each threshold
lr_precision, lr_recall, lr_thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, log_predictions)

#calculate the best threshold
# convert to f score
fscore = (2 * lr_precision * lr_recall) / (lr_precision + lr_recall)
# locate the index of the largest f score
ix = np.argmax(fscore)
print('Best Threshold=%f, F-Score=%.3f' % (lr_thresholds[ix], fscore[ix]))

# calculate precision and recall for each threshold
lr_precision, lr_recall, lr_thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, log_predictions)

#calculate the best threshold
# convert to f score
fscore = (2 * lr_precision * lr_recall) / (lr_precision + lr_recall)
# locate the index of the largest f score
ix = np.argmax(fscore)
print('Best Threshold=%f, F-Score=%.3f' % (lr_thresholds[ix], fscore[ix]))

      np.sum(sel_.estimator_.coef_ == 0)))

In [59]:
test_x_new = sel_.transform(x_test_df)
test_selected_features = pd.DataFrame(sel_.inverse_transform(test_x_new), 
                                 index=x_test_df.index,
                                 columns=x_test_df.columns)

#calculate the predicted probabilities
log_predictions1=log_model.predict_proba(test_selected_features)
log_predictions = log_predictions1[:, 1]

# calculate precision and recall for each threshold
lr_precision, lr_recall, lr_thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, log_predictions)

#calculate the best threshold
# convert to f score
fscore = (2 * lr_precision * lr_recall) / (lr_precision + lr_recall)
# locate the index of the largest f score
ix = np.argmax(fscore)
print('Best Threshold=%f, F-Score=%.3f' % (lr_thresholds[ix], fscore[ix]))

lr_precision, lr_recall, lr_thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, log_predictions)

#calculate the best threshold
# convert to f score
fscore = (2 * lr_precision * lr_recall) / (lr_precision + lr_recall)
# locate the index of the largest f score
ix = np.argmax(fscore)
print('Best Threshold=%f, F-Score=%.3f' % (lr_thresholds[ix], fscore[ix]))

Plot Precision-Recall Curve for Final Model¶

The following table summarizes a point estimate of specificity of each model shown above at a threshold with a sensitivity of 0.92.

The logistic regression model with L1 regularization fit using the training dataset with random undersampling of the majority class and c=0.05 had the best performance, with a specificity of 0.56 and a sensitivity of 0.92. The code below creates a precision-recall curve for this model. A precision-recall curve was used rather than ROC curve as the data is imbalanced. Although this is not a strong overall predictor, the overall goal of this project was to maximize sensitivity over specificity.

In [73]:
sel_ = SelectFromModel(LogisticRegression(C=0.05, penalty='l1',solver='liblinear',random_state=1000,max_iter=500))
model=sel_.fit(x_rus, y_rus)
selected_feat = x_rus.columns[(sel_.get_support())]
x_new = sel_.transform(x_rus)
selected_features = pd.DataFrame(sel_.inverse_transform(x_new), 
                                 index=x_rus.index,
                                 columns=x_rus.columns)

log_model=LogisticRegression(random_state=1000,max_iter=500,solver='lbfgs')
log_model.fit(selected_features,y_rus)
test_x_new = sel_.transform(x_test_df)
test_selected_features = pd.DataFrame(sel_.inverse_transform(test_x_new), 
                                 index=x_test_df.index,
                                 columns=x_test_df.columns)

#calculate the predicted probabilities
log_predictions1=log_model.predict_proba(test_selected_features)
log_predictions = log_predictions1[:, 1]

# calculate precision and recall for each threshold
lr_precision, lr_recall, lr_thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, log_predictions)

# plot the precision-recall curves
no_skill = len(y_test[y_test==1]) / len(y_test)
plt.plot([0, 1], [no_skill, no_skill], linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
plt.plot(lr_recall, lr_precision, marker='.', label='Logistic')
# axis labels
plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
# show the legend
plt.legend()
# show the plot
plt.show()

The following table summarizes the 20 features selected for inclusion in this model. Examination of the selected features may help to further understanding of key risk factors for suicide attempt among adolescents. However, this should be interpreted with caution, because, when there is a group of highly correlated variables, logistic regression with L1 regularization tends to select just one of these variables at random.

Training and Evaluating Neural Network Models¶

The following code trains and evaluates neural network models. I trained each set of models using four training datasets: 1) original training data with class weights described above, 2) training data with random undersampling of the majority class, 3) training data with random oversampling of the minority class, and 4) training data resampled using SMOTE + TOMEK.

Note that this code has been updated since the final presentation, so the values presented differ from those in the final presentation. I was able to increase the specificity slightly at a sensitivity of 0.92 compared to that presented in the final presentation.

The initial model trained for each dataset included one hidden layer with neurons equal to the mean of the neuron number in the input (n=478) and the output layer (n=1), which I rounded to 240. This was based on a recommendation online (although perhaps not fully applicable to this model, but, as a novice, it seemed as good of a starting point as any) that: "In sum, for most problems, one could probably get decent performance (even without a second optimization step) by setting the hidden layer configuration using just two rules: (i) number of hidden layers equals one; and (ii) the number of neurons in that layer is the mean of the neurons in the input and output layers." (Source: https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/181/how-to-choose-the-number-of-hidden-layers-and-nodes-in-a-feedforward-neural-netw)

I then edited the following hyperparameters to search for a model with acceptable accuracy and loss functions while avoiding underfitting and overfitting. 1) Learning rate

2) Dropout rate

3) Number of nodes per hidden layer

4) Number of hidden layers

5) Number of epochs

6) Batch size

From some exploratory analysis with the original training dataset using class weights, I determined that a learning rate of 0.0001, a dropout rate of 0.2, 100 epochs, and a batch size of 100 seemed to be a good starting point. During the training of the neural network model, the data was split into 80% training, 20% validation data to allow graphing of the accuracy and loss function history across epochs.

Evaluation of each neural network model with acceptable fit based on the accuracy and loss function graphs was performed with the same testing dataset. The probability threshold for prediction of suicide attempt was shifted to change sensitivity and specificity values, starting with a threshold of 0.5. For each threshold, a confusion matrix was shown, and sensitivity, specificity, precision, F1 score, and accuracy were reported.

The full process that I went through to choose the final neural network model is shown for the training dataset from which it was derived (the original data with class weights) as an example.

In the future, I would like to perform a grid search to find optimal hyperparameters, using a function such as GridSearchCV, but I was unable to figure out how to use this in time for this project. I will discuss this more in the "Future Directions" section at the end of this report.

The following code calculates the class weights described above. The formula for the weight of each class is: ({1/number of observations in class} * total observations)/2.0.

In [74]:
weight_for_0=((1/4642)*(4834)/2.0)
weight_for_1=((1/192)*(4834)/2.0)
class_weight={0:weight_for_0,1:weight_for_1}
print('Weight for non-suicide attempters: {:.2f}'.format(weight_for_0))
print('Weight for suicide attempters: {:.2f}'.format(weight_for_1))

Weight for non-suicide attempters: 0.52
Weight for suicide attempters: 12.59

The following code separates the training data into 80% training, 20% validation data. It then creates resampled training datasets using the three methods also applied for the logistic regression with L1 regularization models: 1) random undersampling of the majority class, 2) random oversampling of the minority class, and 3) SMOTE+TOMEK.

Original Data with Class Weights¶

This is the starting neural network trained using the original data with class weights. It has a single hidden layer with 240 nodes, a learning rate of 0.0001, a dropout rate of 0.2, 100 epochs, and a batch size of 100. All hidden layers utilize the 'relu' activation function. In the output layer, the 'sigmoid' activation function is used to keep the output in the range of probabilities (0 to 1). An Adam optimizer seemed to perform well during exploratory analyses and was used for all models.

In [78]:
def seed_everything(seed):
    np.random.seed(seed)
    os.environ['PYTHONHASHSEED'] = str(seed)
    tf.random.set_seed(seed)
    
N_FEATURES=len(x_train_df.columns)
    
seed_everything(1000)

model = model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(240, activation="relu")),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.2),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])

model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.0001), loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                  metrics=["accuracy"])

history=model.fit(x_train_df, y_train, epochs=100, batch_size=100, verbose=0,
                        validation_split=0.2, shuffle=True, class_weight=class_weight)

# summarize history for accuracy
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

The following examples served as good metrics for loss curves showing underfitting/overfitting. Source: https://machinelearningmastery.com/learning-curves-for-diagnosing-machine-learning-model-performance/

Underfitting:¶

"A plot of learning curves shows underfitting if:

-The training loss remains flat regardless of training.

-The training loss continues to decrease until the end of training."

Overfitting:¶

"A plot of learning curves shows overfitting if:

-The plot of training loss continues to decrease with experience.

-The plot of validation loss decreases to a point and begins increasing again."

Good fit¶

"A plot of learning curves shows a good fit if:

-The plot of training loss decreases to a point of stability.

-The plot of validation loss decreases to a point of stability and has a small gap with the training loss."

Note that the validation loss may be less than the training loss due to the dropout. This is of importance in my examples, particularly since some of my models have high dropout rates. One online source states, "If you are using dropout regularization layer in your network, it is reasonable that the validation error is smaller than training error. Because usually dropout is activated when training but deactivated when evaluating on the validation set." (Source: https://stats.stackexchange.com/questions/187335/validation-error-less-than-training-error#:~:text=One%20possibility%3A%20If%20you%20are,evaluating%20on%20the%20validation%20set). Additional online sources state the same.

Evaluation of learning curve for original model¶

From the learning curve above (shown below for reference), the training curve appeared to still be decreasing, suggesting a possible underfit. I increased the learning rate to 0.001 to try to improve the fit.

In [87]:
def nn_predict(threshold):
    predictions_df1=pd.DataFrame(nn_predictions)
    predictions_df=predictions_df1.rename(columns={0: 'probability'})
    #print(predictions_df)
    predictions_df['suicide_attempt'] = np.nan
    predictions_df['suicide_attempt'] = np.where(predictions_df['probability']>=threshold, 1, 0)
    final_predictions=predictions_df['suicide_attempt']

    c=confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions_df['suicide_attempt'])
    recall=c[1,1] / (c[1,1] + c[1,0])
    precision=c[1,1]/(c[0,1]+c[1,1])
    print('Confusion matrix when threshold=',threshold,'\n',c)
    print('Sensitivity/recall when threshold =',threshold, ':', recall)
    print('Specificity when threshold =',threshold, ':', c[0, 0] / (c[0, 1] + c[0, 0]))
    print('Precision when threshold =',threshold,':',precision)
    print('F1 Score when threshold =',threshold,':',(2*precision*recall)/(precision+recall))
    print('Accuracy when threshold =',threshold,':',(c[0,0]+c[1,1])/(c[0,0]+c[0,1]+c[1,0]+c[1,1]))
    print('\n')
    return 

nn_predict(0.50)
nn_predict(0.40)
nn_predict(0.35)
nn_predict(0.30)
nn_predict(0.20)
nn_predict(0.10)
nn_predict(0.05)
nn_predict(0.01)
nn_predict(0.005)
nn_predict(0.004)
nn_predict(0.003)
nn_predict(0.002)

#Nodes=50; Dropout Rate=0.3  
seed_everything(1000)

model = model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(50, activation="relu")),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])

model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                  metrics=["accuracy"])

history=model.fit(x_train_df, y_train, epochs=100, batch_size=100, verbose=0,
                        validation_split=0.2, shuffle=True, class_weight=class_weight)

# summarize history for accuracy
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

final_model_eval=model.evaluate(x_test_df, y_test, batch_size=100)
print("Loss is:",final_model_eval[0])
print("Accuracy is:",final_model_eval[1])

#Nodes=150; Dropout Rate=0.5; Epochs=100; Batch Size=50
seed_everything(1000)

model = model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(150, activation="relu")),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])

model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                  metrics=["accuracy"])

history=model.fit(x_train_df, y_train, epochs=100, batch_size=50, verbose=0,
                        validation_split=0.2, shuffle=True, class_weight=class_weight)

# summarize history for accuracy
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

I again examined specificity when sensitivity was equal to 0.92. Specificity was lower when sensitivity was equal to 0.92 (0.31) than in the last model that I tried (0.45), so I stayed with the last model. I will edit each portion of the last model (Nodes=100; Dropout Rate=0.5; Epochs=100; Batch Size=50) up and down while leaving the rest of the model the same to see if it improves performance. If not, I will stick with that model.

1) Nodes Up: We already know that this does not help (see above)

2) Nodes Down: Did not help (see below)

3) Dropout Rate Up: Helped (see below)

4) Dropout Rate Down: I already played with a lower dropout rate (0.4) and it didn't seem to help (see above)

5) Epochs Up: Did not help (see below)

6) Epochs Down: Did not help (see below)

7) Batch Size Up: Did not help (see below)

8) Batch Size Down: Did not help (see below)

Based on this additional analysis, I chose to use the following model: Nodes=100; Dropout Rate=0.6; Epochs=100; Batch Size=50

In [106]:
#Nodes DOWN
#Original model: Nodes=100; Dropout Rate=0.5; Epochs=100; Batch Size=50
#New model: Nodes=50; Dropout Rate=0.5; Epochs=100; Batch Size=50
seed_everything(1000)

model = model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(50, activation="relu")),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.5),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])

model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                  metrics=["accuracy"])

history=model.fit(x_train_df, y_train, epochs=100, batch_size=50, verbose=0,
                        validation_split=0.2, shuffle=True, class_weight=class_weight)

# summarize history for accuracy
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

final_model_eval=model.evaluate(x_test_df, y_test, batch_size=50)
print("Loss is:",final_model_eval[0])
print("Accuracy is:",final_model_eval[1])

#Original model: Nodes=100; Dropout Rate=0.5; Epochs=100; Batch Size=50

seed_everything(1000)

model = model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.6),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation="relu")),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.6),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation="relu")),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.6),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])

model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                  metrics=["accuracy"])

history=model.fit(x_train_df, y_train, epochs=100, batch_size=50, verbose=0,
                        validation_split=0.2, shuffle=True, class_weight=class_weight)

# summarize history for accuracy
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
plt.title('model accuracy')

plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

This did not help with specificity at sensitivity=0.92 (new model: 0.52 vs. old model: 0.54).

My final model after this process is shown below.

Evaluation of Final Neural Network Model¶

My final model had a single hidden layer with 100 nodes, a dropout rate of 0.6, a learning rate of 0.001, 100 epochs, and a batch size of 50. It was fit using the original training data with class weights. At a sensitivity of 0.92, the model had a specificity of 0.54.

Precision-Recall Curve for Final Neural Network Model¶

The code below creates a precision-recall curve for the final neural network model.

In [125]:
model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.6),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation="relu")),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.6),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])

model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), loss='binary_crossentropy', 
                  metrics=["accuracy"])

model.fit(x_train_df, y_train, epochs=100, batch_size=50, verbose=0,
                        validation_split=0.2, shuffle=True, class_weight=class_weight)

nn_predictions=model.predict(x_test_df)

predictions_df1=pd.DataFrame(nn_predictions)
predictions_df=predictions_df1.rename(columns={0: 'probability'})
predictions_df['suicide_attempt'] = np.nan
predictions_df['suicide_attempt'] = np.where(predictions_df['probability']>=0.0024, 1, 0)
final_predictions=predictions_df['suicide_attempt']
    
# calculate precision and recall for each threshold
nn_precision, nn_recall, nn_thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_test, predictions_df['probability'])

# plot the precision-recall curves
no_skill = len(y_test[y_test==1]) / len(y_test)
plt.plot([0, 1], [no_skill, no_skill], linestyle='--', label='No Skill')
plt.plot(lr_recall, lr_precision, marker='.', label='Logistic')
# axis labels
plt.xlabel('Recall')
plt.ylabel('Precision')
# show the legend
plt.legend()
# show the plot
plt.show()

Feature Importance for Final Neural Network Model¶

The code below creates a list of the 50 most important features from the final neural network model.

In [128]:
from tensorflow.keras.wrappers.scikit_learn import KerasClassifier, KerasRegressor
import eli5
from eli5.sklearn import PermutationImportance
In [129]:
def base_model():
    tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.6),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(100, activation="relu")),
        tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.6),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid"))
    ])
    
    model.compile(optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate = 0.001), loss='binary_crossentropy', metrics=["accuracy"])

    return model

my_model = KerasRegressor(build_fn=base_model,epochs=100, batch_size=50, verbose=0, class_weight=class_weight, 
                          validation_split=0.2,shuffle=True) 

my_model.fit(x_train_df, y_train)

perm = PermutationImportance(my_model, random_state=1000).fit(x_train_df,y_train)
eli5.show_weights(perm, feature_names = x_train_df.columns.tolist(),top=50)

The following table includes a description of the 10 most important features.

I tried similar processes as the one demonstrated above with the three other training data sets, created using resampling methods. None performed better than the model shown above, but I have included the final models that I arrived at for each training dataset below. I particularly struggled to fit a model using the training dataset constructed by randomly undersampling the majority class. Note that better performing models may exist because I did not perform a formal grid search. As mentioned previously, I would like to do so in future work with this project.

seed_everything(1000)

model = model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        tf.keras.layers.Input(N_FEATURES),

        tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.35),
        tfa.layers.WeightNormalization(tf.keras.layers.Dense(10, activation="relu")),

    ])

                  metrics=["accuracy"])

history=model.fit(x_stomek_nn,y_stomek_nn, epochs=50, batch_size=10, verbose=0,
                        validation_data=(x_valid_stomek,y_valid_stomek),shuffle=True)

# summarize history for accuracy
plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'])
plt.title('model accuracy')
plt.ylabel('accuracy')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

# summarize history for loss
plt.plot(history.history['loss'])
plt.plot(history.history['val_loss'])
plt.title('model loss')
plt.ylabel('loss')
plt.xlabel('epoch')
plt.legend(['train', 'valid'], loc='upper left')
plt.show()

final_model_eval=model.evaluate(x_test_df, y_test, batch_size=10)
print("Loss is:",final_model_eval[0])
print("Accuracy is:",final_model_eval[1])

Future Steps¶

1) Consider additional classification methods

-I briefly explored random forest classification where working on this project. Given that this was very early exploration, the models are not shown, but I currently have similar sensitivity/specificity as the models shown above. I need to explore this more.

-I could also try other ensemble learning methods.

2) Consider alternate cost-sensitive learning strategies

-Alternate class weights

-Investigate alternate metrics (such as F2 score shown in figure below) to maximize sensitivity while limiting the impact on specificity

-Use parameter tuning functions to find hyperparameters that maximize sensitivity, F2 score, or another appropriate metric (GridSearchCV, etc.)

3) Consider variables other than adolescent self-reported factors

The figure below shows a decision tree to use to determine the best metric to evaluate models on during binary classification. Using this tool, I would like to investigate choosing my model using F2 score in future work. (Source: https://machinelearningmastery.com/framework-for-imbalanced-classification-projects/)

Conclusions¶

The following summaries the performance of Hill et. al's classification tree model, my logistic regression with L1 regularization model, and my neural network model. As you can see, my models do not perform better than Hill et al.'s models and require additional unique pieces of information (20 features for the logistic regression model and the full dataset for the neural network). However, as I described in the "Future Steps" section above, additional research can be performed to investigate whether an alternate model may still be able to perform better than Hill et al.'s classification tree model to predict suicide attempts in a nationally representative sample of US youth.
